<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n25187d"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n25" href="#n25187d">N25 (VI.B.15)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n25all.htm#n25187d"> 187(d)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> crucifix / bells, light in air</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">Relics began to be adored in the fourth century. <mark>Bells</mark> were then introduced in the West, and the earliest liturgies belong to the same age. In the fifth century <mark>incense and lights</mark> were first used by Christians, and the <mark>crucifix</mark> began to be known in the West: in the sixth, sacerdotal vestments began to be distinguishable by the survival of ancient patrician and sacred robes; holy water was used, and miraculous images were adored. <small> Claude R. Conder, <a name="CRRM" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#CRRM"><cite title="source">The Rise of Man</cite></a> (1908) 335-6</small></blockquote> <mm class="note">Note: Possibly a reference to Hyperion &ldquo;bells, and larger blooms, / Like floral censers swinging light in air&rdquo;  <br>Raphael transcription: <a name="c14127d" href="c14all.htm#c14127d">VI.C.14:127(d)</a>, <a name="c14127e" href="c14all.htm#c14127e">VI.C.14:127(e)</a> </mm></dd> </dd></dl>
